"(1) He was alone amid the early summer bustle, the metallic tang of coffee lingering on his tongue as he adjusted the name badge pinned awkwardly to his shirt. The crowd thronging the park’s wide lawns was a mosaic of faces—some eager, some distant, all absorbed in the hum of conference chatter. Beneath the open blue sky, sunlight danced on watered grass, dappling the seats of folding chairs set in a rough circle at the center of the gathering.\n\n(2) Benjamin Green watched the shifting patterns of light and movement without really seeing them. Faces blurred into shapes behind his glasses as he sipped his iced tea, feeling the gentle heat crawl across his skin. There was an odd tension in the air, like the moment before a storm, or perhaps the anticipation of something new—something vital—about to be shared.\n\n(3) He glanced at the stage’s makeshift podium, its wooden planks still warm from previous use. A cluster of journalists and students milled restlessly, their voices rising and falling in animated discussion. Benjamin’s hand trembled slightly in his lap, not from nerves but from an unfamiliar flutter in his chest—a feeling that had nothing to do with the weather.\n\n(4) A woman in the third row caught his fleeting eye. She wore a deep green blouse, the color echoing his own. Her hair was pulled back, strands escaping like ribbons in the breeze. Benjamin found himself imagining her standing closer, the scent of her perfume—something wild and sunlit—drifting toward him.\n\n(5) The program was tight, but the panel was all he could focus on. He shifted as Professor Chen began her introduction, her voice crisp and precise. The audience fell in step with her cadence, but Benjamin’s attention slipped every time the speaker mentioned a new breakthrough. His thoughts drifted, not to data but to the hush between words.\n\n(6) Just before his slot, a young man with a camera jostled past, nearly tripping over Benjamin’s feet. “Excuse me!” he muttered, but Benjamin barely heard. The incident pricked at his patience, but what annoyed him more was the quiet hunger in his own throat—a yearning that defied explanation.\n\n(7) At last, his name was called. On the small stage, surrounded by microphones and the hum of expectant silence, Benjamin prepared to discuss the future of the field. His palms pressed together; the weight of countless questions from his peers settled on his shoulders"